<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName LSID="AD4125BA-1160-51CA-9D0E-3E6F18279CE6" authority="(Burm. f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm. f.) Merr.)" baseAuthorityName="Burm. f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm. f.) Merr." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Aerva" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aerva javanica" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="javanica">Aerva javanica (Burm.f.) Juss. ex Schult. (= Aerva persica (Burm.f.) Merr.)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="names">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">on-hnye</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">English</emphasis>
: aerva, kapok bush, snow bush.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="range">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Widespread in drier parts of the tropics and subtropics of the Old World, from Myanmar, India and Sri Lanka westwards through Southwest Asia, across North Africa to Morocco and south to Cape Verde island and Cameroun Uganda and Tanzania to Madagascar. Introduced in Australia and elsewhere.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="use">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Use.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Root</emphasis>
: Paste made and applied to acne-like conditions of the face.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The species is used as a uricant (
<bibRefCitation author="Burkill, HM" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Museum Leaflets, Harvard University" pageId="172" pageNumber="173" refId="B18" refString="Burkill, HM, 1985. The Useful Plants of West Tropical Africa. 2nd Edition. Volume 1, Families A-D. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." title="The Useful Plants of West Tropical Africa. 2 nd Edition. Volume 1, Families A-D. Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew." year="1985">Burkill 1985</bibRefCitation>
); also to treat kidney stones and for inflammation (
<bibRefCitation author="Zafar, M" journalOrPublisher="Brazilian Journal of Medical and Biological Research" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" publicationUrl="http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" refId="B142" refString="Zafar, M, Ahmad, M, Khan, MA, Abbas, A, 2006. Pollen pictorial of some medicinal plants from Pakistan. Ethnobotanical Leaflets 10: 121-128. http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" title="Pollen pictorial of some medicinal plants from Pakistan. Ethnobotanical Leaflets 10: 121 - 128." url="http://opensiuc.lib.siu.edu/ebl/vol2006/iss1/14/" year="2006">Zafar et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The medicinal uses of another member of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forsskal" authorityYear="1775" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Aerva" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aerva" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Aerva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in India are discussed in 
<bibRefCitation author="Jain, SK" journalOrPublisher="Phytotherapy Research" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B50" refString="Jain, SK, DeFilipps, RA, 1991. Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." year="1991">Jain and DeFilipps (1991)</bibRefCitation>
as follows: The whole plant is used for albumin in the urine; infant diarrhea; cholera; and dysentery. The leaf is used for earache; and the root is used for snakebite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
